  "hash": "sha256:a3f7c2e1b09d4561fe832a7c0d5e9b1f4c8a2d6e7b3f0a1c9d5e2b8f4a7c3d1e",
  "signature": "ed25519:b1c4e7a2f09d3561fe832a7c0d5e9b1f4c8a2d6e7b3f0a1c9d5e2b8f4a7c3d1e5f8b2a4c6d9e1f3",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At MRL 5 for a Class III device, SQA must demonstrate a documented configuration management system, version-controlled solver builds, and traceable test suites covering all hemolysis model subroutines. Gradation 4 requires formal SQA plan with independent review records.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (OpenFOAM v8) is maintained under Git version control with tagged release builds. An SQA plan conforming to FDA guidance on software validation was executed, including unit tests for the modified power-law hemolysis subroutine. Independent code review records are archived. Achieved level 4 satisfies the required level 4 threshold."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 4 requires manufactured-solution verification demonstrating solver convergence rates consistent with formal order of accuracy for all governing equations, including the hemolysis transport scalar. Results must be documented with convergence plots and order-of-accuracy tables.",
      "rationale": "Method of manufactured solutions was applied to the Navier-Stokes solver; observed spatial convergence order was 1.87 (expected ~2 for second-order schemes), marginally below the formal order. The hemolysis scalar transport equation was verified separately with an analytical source term but convergence plots showed slight oscillation at coarse meshes. Achieved level 3 falls below the required level 4; this gap is acknowledged in the overall assessment."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At MRL 5, discretization error must be quantified using Richardson extrapolation or equivalent GCI methodology across at least three systematically refined meshes. The grid convergence index must be reported for all primary quantities of interest including hemolysis index, wall shear stress, and pressure rise.",
      "rationale": "Three mesh levels (4.2 M, 12.6 M, 37.8 M cells) were evaluated. Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values of 3.1% for pressure rise and 8.4% for hemolysis index on the fine mesh. The hemolysis index GCI exceeds the 5% target threshold established for Gradation 4, limiting the achieved level to 3. Discretization error remains the primary contributor to total model uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires that experimental test conditions are documented with traceable calibration records for all measurement instruments, and that operating conditions span at least the nominal design point plus boundary conditions representative of VAD use.",
      "rationale": "Experimental hemolysis measurements were performed at five flow-speed operating points covering the VAD clinical range (3–6 L/min, 2400–3600 RPM). Calibration records for the Coulter counter and pressure transducers are archived with NIST-traceable standards. Test fluid (bovine blood, standardized hematocrit 35%) is documented per ASTM F1841. Achieved level 3 meets the required level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 4 requires quantitative comparison metrics (e.g., RMSE, normalized index of agreement) between predicted and measured hemolysis index values, with uncertainty intervals on both simulation and experiment explicitly propagated and reported.",
      "rationale": "Predicted hemolysis index values were compared against experimental measurements at all five operating points. Normalized RMSE was 18.3%, with simulation predictions systematically over-predicting hemolysis by 12–22% relative to experimental values. Experimental uncertainty (±9% at 95% CI) and simulation uncertainty (Monte Carlo 95% CI ±14%) were both reported. The systematic bias and overlap of uncertainty intervals precluded achievement of Gradation 4; level 3 was assigned."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 4 requires explicit mapping between the simulation QoI (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH) and the clinical decision QoI (plasma-free hemoglobin concentration), supported by a documented physiological translation model or regulatory precedent.",
      "rationale": "The primary simulation QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH), which maps directly to plasma-free hemoglobin (pfHb) via the Heuser-Optiz power-law model with published coefficients. The translation from NIH to pfHb is documented in the hemolysis model specification with reference to FDA guidance and peer-reviewed literature. The QoI relevance chain is fully traceable. Achieved level 4 satisfies required level 4."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 4 requires that validation experiments are conducted on the same device geometry and fluid under conditions that span the full clinical operating envelope defined in the COU, with no extrapolation beyond validated conditions.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry using bovine blood, which is an accepted surrogate for human blood in hemolysis studies. However, the clinical COU specifies five operating points of which one (6 L/min at 3600 RPM) falls at the boundary of the validated experimental envelope. Extrapolation at this boundary condition limits the relevance assessment to Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence was monitored via residual norms for all transported quantities. Steady-state residuals for momentum and continuity reached 1e-5; hemolysis scalar residual plateaued at 3e-4, indicating incomplete iterative convergence for the scalar transport equation. Round-off error was assessed as negligible relative to discretization error. The incomplete scalar convergence limits the achieved level to 2, below the required level 3. This factor represents an unresolved gap in the current assessment cycle."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires a documented simulation execution checklist, peer review of boundary condition setup, and independent reproduction of at least one operating point by a second analyst.",
      "rationale": "A simulation execution checklist was developed and applied for all five operating points. Boundary conditions were independently reviewed by a second CFD analyst prior to submission. One operating point (4.5 L/min, 3000 RPM) was independently reproduced by a second analyst using the same mesh and solver settings, with results agreeing within 2% for all primary QoIs. Achieved level 3 meets the required level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 4 requires a systematic sensitivity study demonstrating that the selected turbulence model and hemolysis constitutive model are the most appropriate available choices for the COU physics, supported by literature comparison and quantitative model-form uncertainty bounds.",
      "rationale": "The k-omega SST turbulence model was selected based on literature consensus for rotating machinery flows. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power-law model was used without comparison to alternative formulations (e.g., Faghih-Sharp, Arora). No systematic model-form sensitivity study was conducted across turbulence model families. Model-form uncertainty was not quantified as a distinct contribution separate from parameter uncertainty in the Monte Carlo analysis. These omissions limit the model form assessment to Gradation 2, substantially below the required level 4."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 4 requires that all model input parameters are assigned probability distributions based on measured data or published uncertainty characterizations, and that a global sensitivity analysis (e.g., Sobol indices) identifies the dominant input contributors to output uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification was performed with 500 samples. Input distributions were assigned for hemolysis model coefficients (alpha, beta, C) based on published experimental scatter, fluid viscosity, and inlet velocity profile. However, global sensitivity analysis using Sobol indices was not completed; only one-at-a-time sensitivity was performed. The absence of global sensitivity analysis limits the achieved level to 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires that experimental samples are characterized with respect to biological variability (e.g., donor-to-donor variation in red blood cell fragility) and that sample size is sufficient to estimate experimental uncertainty at the 95% confidence level.",
      "rationale": "Hemolysis experiments were conducted with bovine blood from a single commercial supplier lot. Donor-to-donor variability in red blood cell fragility was not characterized; a single hematocrit value (35%) was used without sensitivity to biological variability. Sample size (n=3 replicates per operating point) was sufficient for basic uncertainty estimation but insufficient to characterize inter-lot variability. Achieved level 2 falls below the required level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires documented justification that experimental input parameters (fluid properties, geometry, boundary conditions) are equivalent or conservatively representative of the clinical COU parameters, with any deviations explicitly identified and their impact assessed.",
      "rationale": "Fluid properties used in experiments (bovine blood at 37°C, hematocrit 35%) are documented as equivalent to clinical human blood per ASTM F1841 and FDA guidance. Pump geometry in experiments matches the FDA generic pump CAD model used in simulation. Inlet flow profiles in simulation were set to match the experimental pump inlet conditions. One deviation — use of a rigid wall assumption in simulation versus compliant tubing connections in experiments — was identified and assessed as having negligible impact on hemolysis predictions based on sensitivity analysis. Achieved level 3 meets the required level 3."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou2-vad-decision",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Following full 13-factor credibility assessment at MRL 5, the assessment team determined that the CFD hemolysis model provides sufficient credibility for regulatory submission under the low assurance level designation. Seven factors were assessed with achieved levels documented; six factors show gaps below required levels, most notably model form (achieved 2, required 4) and numerical solver error (achieved 2, required 3). The conservative over-prediction bias in hemolysis index (12–22%) provides an additional margin of safety for patient protection. Monte Carlo UQ results bound the hemolysis predictions below the absolute clinical threshold at 95% confidence across all five operating points. The assessment team accepted the submission with the understanding that model form uncertainty quantification and global sensitivity analysis are deferred to the next assessment cycle.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
